column168: Description Of Events

column168: XPO Logistics terminal UPO experienced a UN3267 EDTA Acid Tetrasodium Salt 38% release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. column168: XPO Logistics terminal USA experienced a release from a box containing multiple 55-pound poly bags. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 75-pounds of product released impacting a 6' x 15' area of trailer floor due to the closure on the bags being loose. column168: While loading a pallet of lab pack containers onto a trailer at the Veolia 10 day intransit facility in Dayton, OH, a Veolia operator noticed an odor coming from the pallet. Initially, the employee did not see any damaged or wet boxes, so he proceeded to break down the pallet to inspect each box. After breaking down the pallet, a wet Questar box (141G) was discovered. Veolia estimates approximately one quart of liquid was released during the spill, most of which was absorbed by the fiber box. It appears that a bottle of allyl bromide broke in transit leading to the saturation of the box and release of liquid. The small amount of liquid that was released outside of the fiber box remained on the pallet under the box. The leaking box and spill pads used to clean up the spill were overpacked together for continued transportation to the final disposal facility.
column169: Veolia's safety manager will remind the team that when shipping a package containing inner containers of liquid material a sufficient amount of vermiculite or spill dry should be used to cushion the inner containers during transportation. The vermiculite or spill dry must be in a quantity that will be able to absorb the entire contents of the liquid material. The proper amount of cushioning should be used to ensure glass bottles do not break as a truck or trailer travels down the road.

column168: On July 3, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum of nitric acid had a loosened lid and released approximately one half (0.5) gallon of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Works, Inc. (EWI) to remediate the site. Crews inspected the drum and suspected the seal on the lid was faulty. EWI utilized a forklift to place the drum into an over pack drum to be shipped back to the terminal for further evaluation. All released material was neutralized and recovered with absorbents. Impacted absorbents and PPE were placed into a poly liner and removed from the site for disposal.

column168: On July 4, 2023, one (1) 25-pound bag of Jack's Professional 20-10-20 General Purpose (UN1477) that was damaged due to improper securement during loading. As a result, approximately one (1) pound of product was released to the trailer floor and surrounding cargo. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Hull's Environmental Services, Inc. (HES) to remediate the impacted surface. Crews utilized hand tools to collect and containerize all free-standing product. All undamaged cargo was inspected and repalletized for continued processing and shipping by the facility. The collected product, all UN1477-impacted materials, and the one (1) damaged bag were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum for disposal. The drum was properly labeled and possession of the waste was retained by RLC for disposal through their bulk waste stream

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Valve Open
column168: Reported to be releasing vapor and green-yellow crust on the car.  Upon arrival a vapor cloud was present.  Upon further assessment and opening the housing cover, liquid was visibly releasing from between the valve and the 4-bolt flanged cover plate.  One bolt was missing a nut (found on the pressure plate), one nut was loose.  Crew attempted to tighten without stopping the leak.  The crew re-entered and loosened the flange, the leak did not worsen so the flange was removed.  Product was on top of the ball valve and was swirling.  The gasket had a depressed area and was changed out.  The flange was tightened, and the leak continued.  The liquid valve was cycled several times and the flange removed.  The product was no longer moving.  The gasket was flipped over, flange tightened, and the leak stopped.  Upon arrival of the shipper, the flange was removed, the product was removed off the ball valve, filled with water, and ensured the ball valve was secured with no releases.  No releases were observed, no liquid emitted from the ball valve.  A new Teflon gasket was installed, the flange resecured, and the car diverted back to origination.
column169: Ensure that the car is properly secured and ready for release into transportation.

column168: The skid of UN3378 arrived to the terminal with the spill present. There is no evidence of damage to the bag it was contained in. The dock worker who was handling the product and discovered the spill is seeking medical attention due to congestion.
column169: Ensure we are double checking shipments for spills before sending them on. Take caution to read over the bill of lading before handling any products, especially HazMat.
